I will . . . examine what you shall produce, with as much coolness
and respect, as if you had given the priests no provocation; 
as if you were a man of the most unblemished character, . . .

PAGE 44  But power to do good is the true and lawful end of aspiring;
for good thoughts (though God accept them), yet towards men are little better
than good dreams, except they be put in act.

It destroys likewise magnanimity, and the raising of human nature;
for take an example of a dog, and mark what a generosity and courage he will
put on when he finds himself maintained by a man, who to him is instead of
a God, or "melior natura"; which courage is manifestly such as that creature,
without that confidence of a better nature than his own, could never attain;

If you will have a young man to put his travel into a little room,
and in short time to gather much, this you must do . . . let him not stay
long in one city or town, more or less as the place deserveth, but not long;
nay, when he stayeth in one city or town, let him change his lodging from
one end and part of the town to another, which is a great adamant of acquaintance;

Celsus could never have spoken it as a physician, had he not been
a wise man withal, when he giveth it for one of the great precepts of health
and lasting, that a man do vary and interchange contraries;

PAGE 187  It cannot be denied but outward accidents conduce much
to fortune; favour, opportunity, death of others, occasion fitting virtue;
but chiefly, the mould of a man's fortune is in his own hands.

Whosoever hath any thing fixed in his person that doth induce contempt,
hath also a perpetual spur in himself to rescue and deliver himself from scorn;
therefore all deformed persons are extreme bold.

